(d) In'the rare cases where there is no such diaeresis, any of the substitutes mentioned in (b) is allowed in the fourth foot.

(e) The seventh foot must be either a trochee or a tribrach.

(f) A dactyl is seldom followed by an anapaest: see A. (c) above.

(g) A proceleusmatic is rare except in the first and fifth (i.e. the first foot of each hemistich). In this play, however, pro- celeusmatics occur twice in the second foot (618, 957), as well as in the fifth (1069).

(h) The final half-foot consists of a single syllable, long or short (syllaba anceps).

(i) With the exceptions mentioned in A. (f)—where the rule is explained—the line may not end with two iambic words, though endings of the permissible mala‘m—crucem type occur osten, e.g. 915, 1017.

(j) This is the metre ordinarily employed in passages of lively narrative or excited dialogue delivered in recitative (quasi- Cantica: see Introd. 4). More than half the Menaechmi is written in Trochaic Septenarii. It is curious that the first four continuous passages are of 97 lines each.
